ority you enroll in Kerrie-Anne’s Chorus 101 class and sing christian choral works or you go without instruction...I still disagree that singing cannot be taught without religously themed music.&quot;<br>
<br>
If that same Muslim or atheist student wants to pursue a study of choral music and take it into their college years and beyond, it would be at her own great disadvantage not to be versed in certain classic choral works.  I'm not sure how complete your understanding of choral instruction is, but it is true that you cannot teach singing properly without religiously themed music.  If you restricted your study of vocal performance to leider, madrigals, and contemporary secular works you would have no familiarity with counterpoint, fugue, melismas.  Not to mention that some of the very best examples of tonal painting are in religously-themed music.  <br>
<br>
&quot;It is a purely selfish and narrow-minded view to think that just because the majority doesn’t object or the minorities can opt out it is somehow fair.&quot;<br>
I don't believe that's what's happening in the case we're discussing.  If you choose to study voice at the HS or college level you have to know that a complete education requires the study and performance of religoius-themed music.  I don't think it's selfish or narrow-minded to expect choral instruction to include the best of choral works.  Are you so willing to compromise the education of those students who would like to continue the study of music in college?  Would you also strip English classes of all literature mentioning a Xian god?  There's a point at which we throw the baby out with the bath water, dontcha think?<br>
<br>
&quot;[P]raying lyrically&quot;<br>
Now I think you just made that up.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
<br>
-Simone <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mamagadfly>MamaGadfly</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 364<br> <font color=#3333ff>(4/23/03 1:08 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=193.topic&index=22>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Music studies</span><hr size=1> DBC- I understand your argument but disagree that studying choral music with a religious theme to learn (requiem, mismas, etc. perviously mentioned) or even sing them in the middle school and higher grades is very different from forcing all students to pledge that there is a god or pray or participate in religiously based celebrations.<br>
<br>
I have no problem, for example with my chidlren reading bible passages or William Blake poetry, studying the Sistine Chapel or Michelangelo's David anymore than I would them learning Mozart's requiem or Hayden's famous choral piece. It's all about context and delivery. When ANY subject is being approached objectively, presented for it's educational merit and studied rather than used to celebrate or pray it is not a violation as it is a value-added part of the curriculum. I taught about the Crusades, Reformation and rise of Am religions many times and parts of that included reading things like the Luther's Theses, xian poetry, etc. Only if I had led the class in a prayer using one of these or claimed it was the truth or asked it they be read as part of our &quot;All Saint's Day&quot; celebration would it have crossed the line. KWIM? And for the record, both of my children will attend public school--one already does, so all this is very real for me as it is for Trish.<br>
<br>
&quot;Do we criticize our schools for trying to censor education due to secular subject matter, but applaud them for censoring something with religious subject matter?&quot;<br>
<br>
Well, Stacey--these are usually two different groups and I don't agree with the use of censorship in both cases. I'm totally anti-censorship so am pained by the Salinger, Rand and other bannings but the religious subject matter thing is a 1st amendment issue and I would approach it as above. Never ban reading of/discussion/debate of said materials especialy in context of time period/culture being studied, but definitely ban school sponsored religious celebrations and rituals (Xmas pagent, Easter Party/egg hunt, Halloween party, Valentine's party--what a huge money sucking wast of money/sugar that last one is). <br>
<br>
ST <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Sweetpeas mommy</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(4/23/03 1:39 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=193.topic&index=23>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   maybe I am too much of a band/choir geek...</span><hr size=1> I understand how one could make an SOCAS but I do think there is a difference between teaching religion and teaching musical styles that incoporate religious themes. I think Simone explained the issue rather well in her post (she obviously has more musical training than I...I stopped after my first year of college except for singing/playing for fun.). <br>
<br>
I am about as pro-SOCAS and one can get...(us journalism types are like that, LOL) so I am not saying this because I want the schools to teach my children Christianity...far from it. But if one is going to do a serious study of art and music, I don't see how you can avoid religion altogether. Art and music are expressions of the deepest feelings within the human experience and religion (whether one believes in a god or not) has a place in that. Too much of both art and music history (in any culture...not just Western) revolves around the expression of religion and to leave it out ~is~ a form of censorship in my opinion.<br>
<br>
Kerrie-Anne <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Sweetpeas mommy</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(4/23/03 1:44 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=193.topic&index=24>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   maybe I am too much of a band/choir geek...</span><hr size=1> I understand how one could make an SOCAS but I do think there is a difference between teaching religion and teaching musical styles that incoporate religious themes. I think Simone explained the issue rather well in her post (she obviously has more musical training than I...I stopped after my first year of college except for singing/playing for fun.). <br>
