Let me answer your question before it gets too buried...<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>I'm not sure, though, were you saying that you would or would not like your kids to sing secular tunes like &quot;Let it Snow&quot;? I wasn't following what your opinion was of that.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
I would most likely not let my kids sing in a program that had &quot;Let it Snow&quot; in it, but not necessarily because of the content of the song.  I am assuming alot here, but I know that when I was a kid there was a big movement to take God and Jesus out of the school winter program.  Even though God and Jesus were taken out (we sang only secular songs) there were still many references to Christmas.  Like &quot;It's Beginning to Look A Lot Like Chirstmas&quot;  I don't think that God or Jesus are mentioned in that song at all, but it is a reference to the holiday. (Is that even that actual name?)<br>
<br>
We, as Jehovah's Witnesses, do not want to associate with anything that has to do with the holiday of Christmas.  So, if the school has a Chistmas tree up during the performance in the background, I would not approve of my kids participating.<br>
Plus, this may sound lame, but most winter songs have been tied to the Christmas season for so long that it is almost difficult to seperate the secular from the religious, so singing even a secular winter song makes people think that you are singing about the holiday.<br>
<br>
I hope that I answered your question.<br>
<br>
Trish <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> Mony</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(4/23/03 9:10 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=193.topic&index=26>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   re: Trish</span><hr size=1> Thanks, Trish, that's totally explains it--I getcha now.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->     Here's a follow-up, if you don't mind.  And in the interest of full disclosure, let me tell you that I am pagan (also UU), and our family celebrates Solstice (Yule) as our kind of &quot;sacred&quot; holiday--we do Santa and all that as our secular holiday (and the same with Ostara and Easter, Samhain and Halloween).<br>
That said, I wonder how you--or anyone else jump in here--feels about celebrating or acknowledging the natural phenomenon (for want of a better word) of the solstices and equinoxes? These are occurances in nature that we all experience, along with the change of the seasons.  How would you feel about a teacher--who may or may not follow an earth-based spirituality herself--incorporating time to reflect on the change of seasons?  What would or would you not like to see included in a class event like this, if anything?<br>
<br>
-Simone <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#9fb7df><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> M2</span><br> <span class=usertitle>Unregistered User</span><br>   <font color=#3333ff>(4/24/03 3:34 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=193.topic&index=27>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   celebration</span><hr size=1> I am a huge nature fan.  So I think it would be fun for the kids to celebrate the changing seasons or different solstaces, as a way of teaching science and nature.  I think in a subtle way they already do this.  In my sons pre-school class (public special ed) they make different trees at the beginning of each season to match the season.  In my daughters class they make books that they have to illustrate about the different seasons. - Shirene <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=totalfeline>totalfeline</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 152<br> <font color=#3333ff>(4/24/03 6:05 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=193.topic&index=28>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re:Trish</span><hr size=1> Simone,<br>
<br>
I don't have a problem with the teaching of natural seasons.  In fact, like Shirene said the school already teaches some of this.  Now, if you put a spiritual twist into it, like the whole Mother Nature/Mother Earth thing (not trying to be disrespectful, just not sure what terms to use here) where nature has a personality or the earth does, that I don't agree with.  But, the teaching of why the leaves change colors and how plants.<br>
<br>
You said something about &quot;celebrating&quot; the solsitices or equinoxes...This we already do not do by not celebrating Easter or Chirstmas and I don't agree with celebrating any of them.  Acknowledging them is a different thing.  If something happens we automatically acknowledge it and so I wouldn't deny that they happen.  I as a Witness give credit to God that these things happen and these remarkable natural phenomenons are due to Him so He is who I celebrate (for lack of a better term).  I just don't do it in public schools.<br>
<br>
Did any of that make sense, I felt like I got way off track.<!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :D --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/happy.gif ALT=":D"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
